
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

                    INSTALLATION INSTRUCTIONS FOR UINTAH_CFD_CODE

                                    10/21/99

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The only thing that needs special attention when installing UINTAH_CFD_CODE is the debugging plotting routines.  If you wish to ignore these then gmake and gmake remake should compile the code without any problems otherwise do the following steps.


	 The foundation of debugging plotting routines is the PGPLOT Graphics
	  Subroutine Library written by Tim Pearsons, California Institute 
	 of Technology, http://astro.caltech.edu/~tjp/pgplot/.  PGPLOT is not
	 public-domain software. However, it is freely available for 
	 non-commercial use. The source code and documentation are copyrighted
	 by California Institute of Technology, and may not be redistributed or
	 placed on public Web servers without permission. The software is
	 provided ``as is'' with no warranty.
        

Define the path where the Uintah_cfd_code folder lies

            tcsh    
            set SRC = <path to>Uintah_cfd_code
            set PGPLOTSRC = $SRC/Plot_routines/pgplot
            cd $SRC/Plot_routines

1. Copy the distribution file by anonymous ftp from Caltech. This is a
gzipped tar archive:
     
            netscape ftp://astro.caltech.edu/pub/pgplot/pgplot5.2.tar.gz
        
       
2. Unpack the distribution file to create the ``PGPLOT'' folder. 
    
            gunzip pgplot5.2.tar.gz
            tar -xvf pgplot5.2.tar
            rm pgplot5.2.tar
        
        
3. Configure PGPLOT by selecting device drivers from the available list. I've already made the appropriate changes to a configuration file so replace the one that you downloaded. 
    
             cp $SRC/INSTALL_FILES/drivers.list $PGPLOTSRC
             cd $PGPLOTSRC
                         
    
4. Execute the supplied scripts and makefiles to create the library and demonstration programs.  For an SGI move the following configuration file before you compile
    
            cp $SRC/INSTALL_FILES/f77_cc.conf $PGPLOTSRC/sys_irix
            makemake ../pgplot irix
    
    
You should see the following after `make' is finished
            Found drivers GIDRIV NUDRIV PSDRIV TTDRIV WDDRIV XWDRIV
            
Now compile the code with `make' and cleanup the intermediate files

            make
            make clean
            
    
     
5. Install the C binding for PGPLOT, which provides a convenient way to call PGPLOT subroutines from a program written in C or C++. This requires an ANSI C compiler (that understands function prototypes).
        
            make cpg
    
    
6. Run the demonstration programs on your selected devices and verify that they run satisfactorily. You must first set an enviromental variable.
    
            setenv PGPLOT_DIR  <$PGPLOTSRC> #explicitly define it
            setenf PGPLOT_FONT <$PGPLOTSRC> #explicitly define it
            setenv PGPLOT_DEV /XWIN
            
            pgdemo1
            hit return when it asks for Graphics device/type
            
    
7. If you want install the optional documentation files.
    
            make pgplot.html
            make pgplot-routines.tex
            latex pgplot-routines 

     
8. Copy the compiled libraries and header files to the folders that are looked at by the make file
    
            cp $PGPLOTSRC/libcpgplot.a $SRC/Libraries/.
            cp $PGPLOTSRC/grfont.dat $SRC/Libraries/.
            cp $PGPLOTSRC/cpgplot.h $SRC/Header_files/.
            cp $PGPLOTSRC/pgxwin_server $SRC/Libraries/.
        
 
9. Add the following to lines to your .cshrc file
     #...................................................................
     # PGPLOT commands
     # Specify output GIF files width and height
     #...................................................................
            setenv PGPLOT_DIR  <Path to Uintah_cfd_src>/Libraries/                
            setenv PGPLOT_DEV /XWIN
            setenv PGPLOT_GIF_WIDTH 500
            setenv PGPLOT_GIF_HEIGHT 500

    source ~/.cshrc
    
    
    -   Add the following to lines to your .Xdefaults file.
    
     #.......................................................................
     # pgplot resources
     # Set the size of the windows.
     #.......................................................................
     pgxwin.Win.maxColors: 255
     pgxwin.Win.minColors: 10
     pgxwin.Win.acceptQuit: True
 
     pgxwin.win1.geometry:       500x500+0+50
     pgxwin.win2.geometry:       500x500+500+50
     pgxwin.win3.geometry:       450x450-0-6
     pgxwin.win4.geometry:       450x450+502-8
     pgxwin.win5.geometry:       450x450+30-2
     #....................................................................... 
     
     
    
The package is now installed and you should be ready to go !  If you want you can 
remove the pgplot directory, however, I wouldn't recommend it since you might want
to tweak or add to the plotting capabilites.



-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Platform specfic issues
